₋	[14] social infrastructure projects have been implemented, benefiting 5,734 rural populations (51% women) of Muynak, Takhtakupir and Shumanay districts through improved access to drinking water, electrification, educational and WASH facilities for rural schoolchildren.
₋	[9] (3 initiated by female) innovative business projects have been established, which enabled to create [50] job places (out of which [27] for females) in Muynak, Takhtakupir and Shumanay districts (including a mini-laundry shop, cold room for fruits and vegetables, expanding the capacity of a fish farm, food processing workshops like halva production, chips production, dried fruits). In overall, the income generation projects covered over 30,000 (40% women) direct and indirect beneficiaries. UN Joint Programme staff and Ms. Ulbosin Annabaeva, project beneficiary from Takhtakopir district have participated at the Central Asian Forum for Women Empowerment on November 1-2, 2019, whereas UN Joint Programme’s experience best practices on Women Economic Empowerment have been shared with other participants.
₋	This activity is covered by parallel funding Adaptation project through workshops and round tables: Field workshop with theoretical and practical sessions on “Landscape level adaptation measures to climate change, the best practices of climate resilient conservation agriculture and irrigation methods in the conditions of water deficiency” (Vfq 2019) and Round table “Towards the transition of Aral Sea region from disaster prone zone to zone of innovations and sustainable development (Agriculture sector)”/UNDP -Uzhydromet joint project and “Measures on rational utilization of land resources in northern districts of Karakalpakstan”. Overall participation above 300 people (50% female)
 -	UN JP staff participated in 1st Uzbek-Israeli Agroforum and Agricultural Transformation, Food Security and Nutrition in Central Asia. Global and regional agricultural challenges and new trends are discussed at the events; Over [40] local agricultural specialists and farmers trained on innovative methods of agriculture (laser leveling, drip irrigation, green house management, etc.).
-	In two water distributions centers (Makpalkol and Daukara) 2 self management groups were created and 16 locals have been trained. the best practice is being disiismanated to the Beltau community within the upcoming MPHSTF project.
₋	Based on the updated Impact Assessment methodology, the project has conducted assessment of the impact of the selected projects. The report documents the success stories depict the past and present living conditions of people in affected communities. The report in the form of a Brochure were disseminated among national and development partners at the Government led International Conference on “Obod Mahalla” and “Obod Kishlok”. Results of independent impact assessment of the Income Generation Projects (established since 2017) conducted in November 2019, showed that 12 projects established as a small production facilities are acting as new sources of economic growth; More than 200 rural people have built inter-district economic value-chain networks in their production and service delivery; Most of the beneficiary income level increased on average 13-14%; In 2 districts agriculture producers have enhanced their food storage facilities, resulting in price balance between producers and buyers; 22 projects have expanded their production capacity on average 10% and applied for bank loan for further scale-up.
₋	Under UNDP UNV part, in November 2019, the UN JP team has conducted Final Impact Assessment in 10 target districts of the Republic of Karakalpakstan. It was envisioned to assess the knowledge of populations on specific diseases and their case management actions on 4 major project health interventions: (i) respiratory infections; (ii) cardio-vascular diseases, (iii) gastro-intestinal diseases; (iv) mother and child health. The assessment has been implemented jointly with MOH Karakalpakstan and deployed 10 survey interviewers, 1 Data Management Specialist and 2 Data Entry Operators. The survey covered 1,271 respondents from 10 districts and 10 focus group discussions. The results of the Final Impact Assessment have been compared with the results of 2017 Baseline Assessment. As a result of awareness raising activities by 2,081 Community Health Volunteers throughout the programme cycle, the knowledge of population has increased significantly to compare with 2017 Baseline results. For instance, number of respondents who know 4 major respiratory infections has increased to 23%; 3 major cardio-vascular diseases increased up to 29%; 5 major gastro-intestinal diseases increased to 12,6% and so on.
₋	[3] Town hall meetings were conducted to share the findings of the assessment as well as further promote the human security approach& MPHSTF. At the meetings the concept, structure and role of MPHSTF presented at the grassroots levels; Reps of MIFT, CM have also taken part at the town hall meetings;
