₋	The Presidential resolution issued on 8th January 2019 on supporting the activities of the newly established MPHSTF. The Gov’t has transferred its 1st installment in the amount of $ 2million. As part of this resolution the ‘Roadmap’ has been also endorsed that outlines the specific activities to be conduct for fostering the MPHSTF’s work including the resource mobilization activities. In January, over 80 letters signed by the Deputy Prime Minister of Uzbekistan and sent out via MFA with the call for cooperation. In November 11, 2019, Republic of Uzbekistan and the European Commission signed Financial Agreement on EU Contribution to the Multi-Partner Human Security Trust Fund for the Aral Sea region (5.2 million euros), in Brussels.
₋	A Memorandum of Understanding was signed between the Ministry of Investments and Foreign Trade and the European Investment Bank on allocation of a soft loan in the amount of € 100 mln. for sustainable environmental development of the Aral Sea region in Uzbekistan during the visit of the Vice President of the Bank V. Hudak to Uzbekistan (September 23-25, 2019). Following the MoU, the next step towards the investment program will be the approval of the loan by the EIB. Once approved and signed, the program will be implemented in partnership with the Government of Uzbekistan and the European Union, within the framework of the United Nations Multi-Partner Human Security Trust Fund for the Aral Sea Region.
-	The MPHSTF technical secretariat conducts regular consultations with the UN MPTF office. This resulted in timely preparation of the necessary binding documents to launch the MPHSTF and conduct 1st 2 Steering Committee meetings during the 1st half of 2019;
-	Structures of the MPHSF Steering Committee (represented by the Gov’t, UN, Donor Community, and CSOs) and technical secretariat are formulated and endorsed at the 1st meeting of the MPHSTF Steering Committee held on January 24, 2019. The Tashkent Office team of the UN Joint Program for the Aral Sea region was appointed as the temporary Technical Secretariat till the end of 2019;
-	During the reporting period, 3 - MPHSTF Steering Committee meetings were held. At the 1st meeting held on January 24, 2019, the structure and composition of the MPHSTF Steering Committee (represented by the Gov’t, UN, Donor Community, and CSOs) and Technical Secretariat are formulated and endorsed. The 2nd Steering Committee meeting was held on June 3, 2019. Following results of the meeting, 2 proposals for the total amount of USD 3.1 mln. were approved for funding. The 3rd Steering Committee meeting was held in December 16, 2019 to decide on the date and priority areas for the Second Call for Proposals. Decision was made to conduct Second Call for Proposals on January 29, 2020. In addition, concept of Advisory Committee on Sustainable Development of the Aral Sea region of Uzbekistan on the platform of the MPHSTF was discussed and the decision was made on its establishment. 
-	In January 2019 the Government of the Republic of Uzbekistan sent appeals addressed to more than 80 heads of governments of donor countries, international financial organizations, transnational corporations and private philanthropists with a proposal for cooperation within the framework of the UN Trust Fund for the Aral Sea region. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs, together with the Ministry of Investments and Foreign Trade, identified 17 priority donor countries for which individual “Road maps” were developed to work out how to attract their funds and ensure participation in the Trust Fund.
On March 22, 2019, a side event on “Partnership for People: UN Multi-Partner Human Security Trust Fund for the Aral Sea Region in Uzbekistan”, initiated by the Government of the Republic of Uzbekistan and the UN Office in Uzbekistan was organized with the support of the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) on the margins of the Regional Forum on Sustainable Development in Geneva (Switzerland). The representatives of a number of UN agencies, member-states permanent missions to the UN in Geneva, diplomatic corps and other participants of the Forum participated in the event, where the MPHSTF was presented in detail to further galvanize coordinated donor support to the Aral Sea region.
On 23-25 October 2019, the Uzbek delegation has taken part in the Climate Change Submit in NY and conducted bilateral meetings to galvanize the donor funds to the Aral Sea region through the MPHSTF. In addition, the SDG Integration Team from UNDP HQ and RBAP had series of meetings with the representatives of key government officials at national and regional level, discussed the potential opportunities and challenges around the Aral Sea Region and developed Concept Note for a high-level International Conference on the “Aral Sea Region – Zone of Ecological Innovation and Technology”, that was held on October 24 2019 to gain further international support.
-	As per the decision of the 1st MPHSTF Steering Committee meeting, the 1st call for proposals were launched in March 2019, and as result of it, 5 proposals were submitted to the consideration of the Fund. Based on the decision of the 2nd MPHSTF Steering Committee meeting held on 3 June 2019, two proposals for the total amount of USD 3.1 mln were approved to be funded for the Aral Sea region as follows:
The first approved proposal submitted by UNICEF and UNFPA jointly with the Ministry of Health of the Republic of Uzbekistan “Improvement of quality of perinatal care service to most vulnerable mothers and newborns” aims to improve the quality of perinatal care service to most vulnerable mothers and newborns, benefiting estimated 26,000 pregnant women and newborns in Karakalpakstan, while 500 medical workers are expected to improve their skills through dedicated training programmes at the second level perinatal centers . 
The second approved proposal submitted by UNDP and UNESCO in cooperation with a number of local and national stakeholders (including the Ministry of Economy and Industry of the Republic of Uzbekistan, the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Karakalpakstan) “Addressing the urgent human insecurities in the Aral Sea region through promoting sustainable rural development” aims at tackling multiple dimensions of human security, such as providing access to drinking water for over 3,500 rural people, expanding income generation opportunities for vulnerable communities with the primary focus on women and youth through support to SMEs and community level eco-tourism development (benefiting 250 men and women), as well as promoting climate change adaptation actions through evidence based afforestation initiatives in the dried bed of the Aral Sea (with direct beneficiaries estimated at 1850 people, and indirectly benefiting more than 300,000, people). The proposal approved by the MPHSTF will be implemented in the Takhtakupir district of the Republic of Karakalpakstan, with the population of 39,7 thousand people. 
-	Training materials on Human Security Concept in Russian/Uzbek languages were updated and disseminated at national level in collaboration with the experts from the Academy of Public Administration under the President of Uzbekistan. 
₋	Based on the developed materials, trainings to further promote the HS were conducted at national, regional, local and community levels covering over 200 participants. To raise the awareness of human security concept, following materials were produced and widely disseminated to target audiences, i.e.: 1.Animation to promote UN JP activities; 2.Short (4 min.) video film on MPHSTF and Aral Sea crisis demonstrated at the UN High-level side event on the margins of 73rd session of the UN GA and countrywide by national and local TV-channels; 3.Investment Guide Invest in Karakalpakstan; 4.UN MPTF Fact-sheets 5.Infographics MPHSTF Advantages; 6. Four animation on health promotion; 7. Documentary Film about community health volunteering work in mainstreaming health security. In the course of call for proposals for funding through MPHSTF, different information outlets were used to delivery information about the human security concept and MPHTSF to the target groups including the gov’t officials and population of the Aral Sea region. Group of officials from the Ministry of Investment and Foreign Trade and Council of Ministers have visited remote communities and jointly with UN JP team held town hall meetings to share information about the human security concept and MPHSTF.
-	In line with the Communication strategy developed by the Programme, the key activities and events were actively promoted through various mass media sources, including national television and radio broadcastings, print media (newspapers and magazines), internet resources (sites of news agencies, official sites of organizations, social media platforms and blogs with a necessary target audience). Various seminars and outreach sessions, workshops and roundtables, brochure, Post Show Reports, newsletter, one-pagers, infographic, calendar, video and audio interviews, as well as a documentary helped to raise awareness about the profile of the Programme. Moreover, to increase public awareness on the Joint Programme and its activities with focus on the human security concept tailored outreach instruments were used to various partner categories to ensure the greater effect: government, international community, population (national level), mass media, beneficiaries, expert community, and business.
₋	National Consultant has been recruited on researching of the existing policy and legislative frameworks and identification of gaps and barriers that may hamper implementation of HS approach is under process. The consultant has provided Report on Further Interventions to Implement Human Security Concept in Uzbekistan, specifically recommending the mainstreaming the human security concept through the State Programmes such as Obod Kishlok and Obod Makhalla . The best-practices of the Programme and Brochure to promote the Human Security Concept were disseminated among national and development partners at the Government led International Conference on “Obod Mahalla” and “Obod Kishlok”.The best-practices of the UN Joint Programme on the application of the human security concept in the Aral Sea region was showcased at different events including at the International Conference related to the Aral Sea Issues held in October 2019 as well as the Govt organized International Conference “Programs “Obod Kishlok” and “Obod Mahalla”: the First Achievements and Prospects”, and shared the best-practices on the application of the human security concept and its advantages on promoting the sustainable rural development as well as published the Brochure on documenting the best-practices of the human security approach in addressing the needs of the people, which was disseminated among the conference participants. 
-	The UNDP CPD Output “1.3. Integrated, multi-sector and multi-level approach established to mitigate human security risks for communities affected by Aral Sea disaster” and UNCT UNDAF Outcomes contain human security concept and terminology. 
₋	Organization of the high level visits of the representatives of the EU to showcase the Programme results; Support to Gov’t delegations’ visits to the USA, Japan, Brazil and Germany to promote the MPHSTF to mobilize the resources; Organization of the visits of High level UN officials - UNDP SA, and UNDP RRs in order to expand global focus to Aral region and needs on consolidated efforts through human security concept. In addition, the MPHSTF Strategy is built based on the HS concept. Thus, the HS is promoted at all levels in the course of negotiations with the development partners and government to mobilize the resources for the Aral Sea region. In addition, UNDP and UNFPA proposal UNDP-UNFPA Joint Project “Building the Resilience of Local Communities Against Health, Environmental and Economic Insecurities Caused by Environmental Destruction in the Aral Sea Region” with USD 3,211,618 budget have been approved for funding by the Government of Japan for duration of 2 years (Oct 2019-Sep 2021). Thus, UNDP will continue to promote human security approach through MPHSTF and by implementation of aforementioned joint projects.

Programme Exit Strategy/Sustainability Plan:

- Operationalization of the MPHSTF, issue of the Presidential degree. The Fund’s Strategy is based on the HS concept, aims at addressing the Aral Sea crisis (institute sustainability);
- Launch of 3 joint projects with over 6 million USD with participation of (UNDP, UNFPA, UNICEF, UNESCO) to address the environmental, social, economic and health insecurities in the Aral Sea region, that replicates and upscales the JP best-practices;
- On-going UNDP support for SDG Integration in the Aral Sea Region and the importance of implementing a Systematic Approach to Addressing Complex Problems in the Aral Sea Region;
- Knowledge sharing and support to the Innovation Centre for the Aral Sea region and UNDP Acceleration Lab to promote and advocate for evidence-based new innovative approaches for development;
- Institutionalization of community health volunteering through the Nurses Association at the Ministry of Health of Karakalpakstan.

